She undoubtedly has strong traits of both antisocial and narcissistic personality disorder. Whether it's enough to set a diagnosis... I'd bet 'yes', if she was about to be examined for it and anyone would take my bet.

People like this lie often, and without moral qualms. This does make them better and more practiced liars than they would otherwise be. However, it doesn't make them more intelligent, meaning that they can still get confused and be trapped in contradictions. They also have the handicap that they often don't understand normal emotional reactions, and might end up making peculiar claims, either because they don't know what a normal person would say, or because they don't know how normal people will react to what they say. Finally, and most importantly in the context of a legal deposition, they're not immune to fear and stress about losing control of a situation. They can remain calm in situations where someone else is in trouble, and are often calm even when their own safety is at risk, but the absolutely hate losing control.

A highly intelligent person with antisocial or narcissistic personality disorder will almost always be a very skilled liar. Less intelligent ones will be surprisingly skilled in some situations, and surprisingly unskilled in others. There'll often be something "hard-to-define-but-definitely-off" about them, though, even when their lies are very good.
